on":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The biggest factor affecting how collectively intelligent a group can be is the degree of coordination among its members – Anita Woolley","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe biggest factor affecting how collectively intelligent a group can be is the degree of coordination among its members, says Anita Woolley, a leading expert in organisational behaviour at Carnegie Mellon University. Smart tools can be a boon in this area, which is why Woolley is working with colleagues to develop AI-powered coaches that can track group members and provide prompts to help them work better as a team.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;The roles these [AI] tools can play are virtually endless,&rdquo; says Woolley. &ldquo;Fostering communication among the different components, reminding people of stuff they might have forgotten, being a repository of information, helping the group coordinate its decision making.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08d0718"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"bees flying","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHive minds\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThere are already promising examples of how AI can help us better pool our unique capabilities. San Francisco start-up Unanimous AI has built an online platform that helps guide group decisions. They&rsquo;ve looked to an unlikely place to guide their AI: the way honeybees make collective decisions.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We went back to basics and said, &lsquo;How does nature amplify the intelligence of groups?&rsquo;,&rdquo; says CEO Louis Rosenberg. &ldquo;What nature does is form real-time systems, where the groups are interacting all at once together with feedback loops. So, they're pushing and pulling on each other as a system, and converging on the best possible combination of their knowledge, wisdom, insight and intuition.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"What nature does is form real-time systems, where the groups are interacting all at once together with feedback loops – Louis Rosenberg","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ETheir Swarm AI platform presents groups with a question and places potential answers in different corners of their screen. Users control a virtual magnet with their mouse and engage in a tug of war to drag an ice hockey puck to the answer they think is correct. The system&rsquo;s algorithm analyses how each user interacts with the puck &ndash; for instance, how much conviction they drag it with or how quickly they waver when they&rsquo;re in the minority &ndash; and&nbsp; uses this information to determine where the puck moves. That creates feedback loops in which each user is influenced by the choice and conviction of the others allowing the puck to end up at the answer best reflecting the collective wisdom of the group.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESeveral academic papers and high-profile clients who use the product back up the effectiveness of the Swarm AI platform. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002F11s1ty2quyfy2qbmao3bwxzc-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002F2019\u002F09\u002FForecasting-Financial-Markets-by-Swarm-IEEE-HCC-2019.pdf\"\u003EIn one recent study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a group of traders were asked to forecast the weekly movement of several key stock market indices by trying to drag the puck to one of four answers &mdash; up or down by more than 4%, or up and down by less than 4%. With the tool, they boosted their accuracy by 36%.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ECredit Suisse has used the platform to help investors forecast the performance of Asian markets; Disney has used it to predict the success of TV shows; and Unanimous has even partnered with Stanford Medical School to boost doctors&rsquo; ability to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002F11s1ty2quyfy2qbmao3bwxzc-wpengine.netdna-ssl.com\u002Fwp-content\u002Fuploads\u002F2018\u002F09\u002FASI-for-Radiology-IEEE-IEMCON-2018.pdf\"\u003Ediagnose pneumonia\u003C\u002Fa\u003E from chest X-rays by 33%.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08d0717"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"chest x ray","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETeam building\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut designing technology that can mesh well with human teams can be surprisingly difficult, says Woolley, who is working with colleagues to develop AI-powered coaches that can track group members and provide prompts to help them work better as a team.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fci.acm.org\u002F2019\u002Fassets\u002Fproceedings\u002FCI_2019_paper_7.pdf\"\u003Eone study\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, her team tried out three different tools designed to maximise collective intelligence: one that gave real-time feedback on team members&rsquo; effort, another that helped divide and assign tasks and a chatbot that helped the group talk about their skills and expertise.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"It's easier to be harmful or to create things that annoy people than it is to create things that are honestly helpful – Anita Woolley","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe first tool appeared to demotivate people, while the second ended up distracting teams with unnecessary planning. Only the final tool helped, by ensuring the best-suited people worked on each task. &ldquo;What we keep discovering is that it's easier to be harmful or to create things that annoy people than it is to create things that are honestly helpful,&rdquo; says Woolley.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIt is still really difficult to build AI with social intelligence, she says, because machines continue to struggle to pick up the nuanced social cues that guide so much of group dynamics. It&rsquo;s also evident from Woolley&rsquo;s research that these kinds of systems only work if humans truly trust AI decision making, and if users are only receiving gentle nudges from the system. &ldquo;As soon as it's heavy handed, people are looking for ways to disable it,&rdquo; says Woolley.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08d0715"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"robot with people","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-11"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut the reasons why it can be hard to combine machines and humans are also central to why they work so well together, says Baeck. AI can operate at speeds and scales far out of our reach, but machines are still a long way from replicating human flexibility, curiosity and grasp of context.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nesta.org.uk\u002Freport\u002Ffuture-minds-and-machines\u002F\"\u003Erecent report\u003C\u002Fa\u003E Baeck co-authored with Nesta senior researcher Aleks Berditchevskaia identified a number of ways AI could enhance our collective intelligence. This includes helping make better sense of data, finding better ways to coordinate decision making, helping us overcome our inherent biases and highlighting unusual solutions that are often overlooked.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut the report also showed that combining AI tools with human teams requires careful design to avoid unintended consequences. And there is currently a dearth of research into how groups react to being corralled by AI, says Berditchevskaia, making it hard to predict how effective these systems will be in the wild.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;It can potentially stretch us in new ways or enhance our speed when we need to be reacting quicker,&rdquo; she adds. &ldquo;But we're still at very early stages of understanding and being able to navigate the individual reactions to those kinds of AI system in terms of issues of trust and how it affects their own sense of agency.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHumanising AI\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOur combined wisdom can also help give a more human element to AI technology, and better guide its decisions.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAt London-based start-up Factmata, which has built an AI moderation system, the company has enlisted more than 2,000 experts, including journalists and researchers, to analyse online content for things including bias, credibility or hate speech. They then used this analysis to train a natural-language processing system to automatically scan web pages for problematic content.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Once you have that trained algorithm it can scale to those millions of pieces of content across the internet,&rdquo; says CEO Dhruv Ghulati. &ldquo;You're able to scale up the critical assessment of those experts.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhile AI is often trained on data labelled by experts in a one-off process, Factmata&rsquo;s experts continually refresh the training data to make sure the algorithms can keep up with the ever-shifting political and media landscape. They also let members of the public give feedback on the AI&rsquo;s output, which Ghulati says ensures it remains relevant and free of bias itself.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEntwining ourselves and our decisions every more tightly with AI is not without risks, however. The synergy between AI and collective intelligence works best the more information we give the machine, says Woolley, which involves difficult choices about how much privacy we&rsquo;re happy to surrender.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-12"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"We can have some very smart individuals working on different components in isolation, but if we don't have coordination it's really hard to make any headway – Anita Woolley","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-13"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EBut given the world&rsquo;s complex multifaceted challenges, such as climate change and pandemics, harnessing our collective intelligence more effectively is essential, she says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThere are already examples of how the approach could tackle these kinds of problems. Researchers at Carnegie Mellon are currently \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fcovidcast.cmu.edu\u002F\"\u003Eforecasting the Covid-19 pandemic in real time\u003C\u002Fa\u003E by using machine learning to combine voluntary symptom surveys, doctors&rsquo; reports, lab statistics and Google search trends. Elsewhere, the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fearlywarningproject.ushmm.org\u002F\"\u003EEarly Warning Project\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in the US has identified countries at greatest risk of atrocities using a combination of crowd-sourced predictions, expert assessments and machine learning algorithms.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We can have some very smart individuals working on different components in isolation, but if we don't have coordination it's really hard to make any headway,&rdquo; says Woolley. &ldquo;I think it's going to be critical to helping these different components actually coordinate in the ways needed to address the biggest collective action problems.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence-14"}],"collection":["worklife\u002Fcolumn\u002Fcollective-intelligence"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-05-14T03:16:35Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"How AI can help us harness our 'collective intelligence'","headlineShort":"How AI can make us all work smarter","image":["p08d0715"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5ec24d8cc1ee0bf63cc3ac8c"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"worklife","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Collaborating usually makes our work better – but keeping a team on task is not easy. Now, researchers are finding that machines can bring out the best in group work.","summaryShort":"Can machines help harness our 'collective intelligence'?","tag":["tag\u002Ftechnology"],"creationDateTime":"2020-05-13T20:08:51.828444Z","entity":"article","guid":"da5edc94-6956-4f53-b5f6-562bd1f52b3a","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence","modifiedDateTime":"2020-05-13T20:08:51.828444Z","project":"worklife","slug":"20200513-how-ai-can-help-us-harness-our-collective-intelligence","cacheLastUpdated":1590533223632},"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong","_id":"5ec24ce0c1ee0bf63cbe2ecf","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["worklife\u002Fauthor\u002Farianne-cohen"],"bodyIntro":"Apologies can be tricky, but combining a dose of gratitude with a gesture that costs you something can help smooth ruffled feelings.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAcademics are sorry that apology research is floundering. New discoveries on apologies rarely appear because the studies are challenging to design, not unlike determining whether woodpeckers get headaches, or boiling the ocean.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ECindy Frantz, a social and environmental psychologist at Oberlin College in the US state of Ohio, has tried. &ldquo;I once tried to run a study where someone was wronged in the lab, but the logistics were very complicated for ethical reasons,&rdquo; she says. &ldquo;You can&rsquo;t do a grievous wrong.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis often leaves researchers who want to study apologies scratching their heads: what wrongs can they ethically inflict on study participants that would necessitate dramatic apologies? Most resort to asking participants hypothetical questions (&ldquo;Imagine that Sam just ran over your foot with his car&rdquo;), or depend on memory, which is notoriously biased and fallible (&ldquo;Tell me about your apology to your mother&rdquo;). This is all further complicated by the cultural specificity of apologies.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EEven so, there is a niche of emerging apology research. Among the researchers finding a way around the experimental difficulty is Yohsuke Ohtsubo, a psychologist at Kobe University. He has spent a dozen years studying sorries around the world, and late last year \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.tandfonline.com\u002Fdoi\u002Ffull\u002F10.1080\u002F17470919.2019.1697745\"\u003Epublished\u003C\u002Fa\u003E the fifth of six papers adding crucial how-to instructions. When apologising, its best to \u003Cem\u003Epay up\u003C\u002Fem\u003E with a gift that is \u003Cem\u003Ecostly\u003C\u002Fem\u003E. For example, a corporation that wrongs customers might repent with pricey gift certificates, or an individual could atone for flaking on a social date by saying, &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to cancel my trip this weekend and spend Saturday with you&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EApology gifts are as old as sin. Ohtsubo&rsquo;s unexpected contribution is that the point of the gift is \u003Cem\u003Enot\u003C\u002Fem\u003E to enrich the recipient.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The gift has to hurt the giver","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;My research shows that it&rsquo;s the cost to the offender that matters,&rdquo; he says. In other words, the gift has to hurt the giver. Ohtsubo&rsquo;s work shows that this holds true among both groups and individuals, in private and public apologies and in countries including the US, South Korea, the Netherlands, Indonesia, Chile, Japan and China. He gives the example of a well-known Japanese singer who atoned to her fans by \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-asia-21299324\"\u003Eshaving off her long hair following an illicit relationship\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, a controversial gesture that demonstrated both how much she valued her career and fans, and that she was &ldquo;unlikely to damage that relationship again&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor those of us who bumble around the planet saying, &ldquo;Oh, I&rsquo;m so sorry!&rdquo;, this presents a paradigm shift: the purpose of apologising is not to say sorry and explain the past, but to signal the value of the relationship and lessons learned, while convincingly promising that the bad behaviour will not be repeated (see: a gift far too costly to procure twice).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E&lsquo;Repairing esteem&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBeyond gifting, the general rules of apologising are straightforward, says Amy Ebesu Hubbard, chair of the department of communicology at the University of Hawai&rsquo;i at Mānoa: accept responsibility, acknowledge harm and suffering, promise future excellence, offer an immediate remedy and express sincerity. The words &ldquo;sorry&rdquo; and &ldquo;apologise&rdquo; should definitely be included. Not all components are necessary for minor transgressions.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08czr97"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAnother \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fdoi.org\u002F10.1177\u002F0022242919889894\"\u003Erecent study in the American Marketing Association&rsquo;s Journal of Marketing\u003C\u002Fa\u003E adds a new guideline: start with &ldquo;thank you&rdquo;, especially in less severe breaches.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;First say, &lsquo;Thank you for your understanding&rsquo; or &lsquo;Thank you for your patience&rsquo;, instead of &lsquo;Sorry for the wait&rsquo;,&rdquo; says lead author Xiaoyan Deng, associate professor of marketing at the Fisher College of Business at The Ohio State University, who ran seven studies with American and Chinese student as well as Amazon workers enduring failed service situations, such as restaurant, purchase and appointment delays. &ldquo;By offering your appreciation for their contributions, you increase their self-esteem. That boost of self-esteem leads to higher levels of satisfaction.&rdquo; She also suggests not rehashing the gaffe, which only cements the screw-up details in people&rsquo;s memories. Instead, implicitly acknowledge it.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs a rule of thumb, thank yous and apologies likely work best in tandem, says Oberlin&rsquo;s Frantz. &ldquo;Feeling valued by others is a very core psychological need, and thanking them would help repair self-esteem,&rdquo; says Frantz. &ldquo;The thanking is about repairing esteem, and the apology is about what the future relationship is going to be like.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOngoing work by Alison Wood Brooks, an associate professor of business administration at Harvard Business School, supports this. She and a colleague are currently studying a trove of apologies at parole hearings for crimes ranging from speeding to murder. She has found that apologies with a promise of good future behaviour are more effective, while apologies that include explanations of why the transgression occurred are ineffective.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EExplanations or excuses for past offenses are to be avoided &ndash; Alison Wood Brooks\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Explanations or excuses for past offenses are to be avoided – Alison Wood Brooks","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFor example, a parole board does not want to hear: &ldquo;I drove drunk because I was exhausted and wanted to leave right then, and I take full responsibility for that poor decision.&rdquo; They want to hear: &ldquo;I plan to attend AA meetings every Tuesday and Friday, and go to the gym with my sponsor on Sundays.&rdquo; Brooks says that her findings &ldquo;suggest that explanations or excuses for past offenses are to be avoided&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETiming matters, too. Frantz&rsquo;s nearly \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.researchgate.net\u002Fpublication\u002F222331911_Better_Late_Than_Early_The_Influence_of_Timing_on_Apology_Effectiveness\"\u003E20-year-old study on the timing of apologies\u003C\u002Fa\u003E is still widely cited, because apologising too quickly fails. &ldquo;The purpose of the apology is to help the victim feel heard and understood, and convince them that the perpetrator is not going to do it again,&rdquo; says Frantz. Thus, apologising before victims have spoken their minds will bomb.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerceptions of sincerity\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EApology experts are amusing to talk to, because they perceive world events as a series of apologies, yet often cannot recall the particulars of the offences. (As Frantz put it: &ldquo;I can&rsquo;t remember the details of the incident, but it was like there was some controversy over how something was handled.&rdquo;) All in this article agree that it is totally useless to evaluate public apologies not aimed at you, which is 98% of them. The classic example is a politician caught cheating on a spouse. The politician typically apologises publicly to constituents, yet within that apology also apologises directly to the wronged spouse. &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a little odd,&rdquo; says Ebesu Hubbard, whose work has shown that observers and apology recipients can perceive the sincerity level of apologies differently. &ldquo;What matters is whether \u003Cem\u003Ethe person receiving it\u003C\u002Fem\u003E thinks its sincere,&rdquo; she says. Not you.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08czr37"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EShe praises Kentucky Governor Andy Beshear, who last week \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fworld-us-canada-52475104\"\u003Ecriticised a scammer for applying for unemployment benefits under the name of late rapper Tupac Shakur\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The Kentuckian, who was in fact legally named Tupac Shakur, did not take this well. &ldquo;Beshear did all the kinds of good things that you would expect in an apology,&rdquo; says Ebesu Hubbard. He first called Shakur to apologise one-on-one, then publicly acknowledged that he had hurt Shakur, took full responsibility and &ndash; crucially &ndash; praised Shakur for his graciousness.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe high mark for corporate apology is still held by KFC, says Edwin Battistella, author of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.amazon.com\u002FSorry-About-That-Language-Apology\u002Fdp\u002F0199300917\"\u003ESorry About That: The Language of Public Apology\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Following a UK shortage of chicken in 2018, KFC \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fnewsbeat-43169625\"\u003Epublished newspaper ads\u003C\u002Fa\u003E with the letters &lsquo;FCK' on a chicken container, above an apology to customers that thanked them for bearing with KFC during their &ldquo;hell of a week&rdquo;. It went viral.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;They did a really good job,&rdquo; says Battistella. &ldquo;They were able to make light of it.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong-8"}],"collection":null,"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-05-13T20:11:34Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Why we've been saying 'sorry' all wrong","headlineShort":"The smart way to say 'sorry'","image":["p08czqgr"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5ec24d8cc1ee0bf63cc3ac8c"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"worklife","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Apologies can be tricky, but combining a dose of gratitude with a gesture that costs you something can help smooth ruffled feelings.","summaryShort":"Why a good apology combines gratitude and a costly gesture","tag":["tag\u002Fpsychology"],"creationDateTime":"2020-05-12T19:51:40.05695Z","entity":"article","guid":"9218b6d1-0df8-4742-b21d-277902248c61","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong","modifiedDateTime":"2020-05-13T01:24:08.005811Z","project":"worklife","slug":"20200512-why-weve-been-saying-sorry-all-wrong","cacheLastUpdated":1590533223632},"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others","_id":"5ec24ce0c1ee0bf63cbe2e18","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":[],"bodyIntro":"In a world of telework, some people just take better to working from home. Does this productivity come naturally, or can you learn it?","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EFor some, working from home is a gift &ndash; a remarkable opportunity to focus and be hyper-productive, all the while finding time to walk the dog and even \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fdustinpari\u002Fstatus\u002F1252775932244484098\"\u003Eexercise in pyjamas\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. For others &ndash; well, the transition isn&rsquo;t quite as seamless. Some find all they&rsquo;ve done with their eight hours is \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002FShirleydocious\u002Fstatus\u002F1255056090783498240\"\u003Eanswer two emails\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Frachelwilson94\u002Fstatus\u002F1253723176028307457\"\u003Edream about a massage\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or discover their &lsquo;\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftwitter.com\u002Fgeoffwhite247\u002Fstatus\u002F1255443096076193792\"\u003Echeese hour&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIt&rsquo;s true: some people simply have dispositions and personality traits that enable them to better adjust to the new world of remote work than others. However, it&rsquo;s not so black and white. You&rsquo;re not necessarily destined to be good or bad at working remotely &ndash; some may just have to put in more effort than others.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe pull of procrastination\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EProcrastination is never easier than when your superior isn&rsquo;t looking over your shoulder. As long as the status light on your communication app is green, it&rsquo;s easy to pop into the kitchen and try a new recipe, or get into a YouTube hole, with no one any the wiser.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIf it feels easier to procrastinate at home than in the office, it is for most: telework is a &ldquo;weak situation&rdquo; with murkier expectations about behaviour, says Timothy Pychyl, associate psychology professor at Carleton University in Ontario. In contrast, he points to a common situation: &ldquo;In an elevator, we all typically &lsquo;act elevator&rsquo;, for example avoid eye contact with others, and keep our distance as [much as] possible &hellip;. The office is more of a strong situation with expectations for many things such as dress codes, arrival and departure times [and] time spent on or off task.&rdquo; Weaker cues and lower accountability may make procrastination more likely at home.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd without the strong situation of an office, it&rsquo;s quite a bit easier to dismiss unpleasant tasks. When there&rsquo;s a task on your plate you don&rsquo;t want to dive into, or you&rsquo;re banging your head against a wall with a tech problem, you&rsquo;re testing your &lsquo;frustration tolerance&rsquo;, says Pychyl. Those who have a lower frustration tolerance are much more likely to procrastinate &ndash; they&rsquo;re the people who get up from their desk and find a distraction.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"People with high frustration tolerances are generally also conscientious workers, who particularly succeed at remote work","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;If you&rsquo;re easily getting frustrated, then you&rsquo;re going to run away from [work] and use avoidance as a coping mechanism, which will shoot you in the foot,&rdquo; says Pychyl.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ENot everyone working at home succumbs to the pull of procrastination, however. Those on the other end of the spectrum push through the work. Pychyl adds that people with high frustration tolerances are generally also conscientious workers, who particularly succeed at remote work. Research has also shown that, of the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fhomepages.rpi.edu\u002F~verwyc\u002FBIGFIVEOH.html\"\u003E&lsquo;Big Five&rsquo; personality dimensions\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, &ldquo;the trait of conscientiousness has been found to be the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpdfs.semanticscholar.org\u002F37ac\u002F20804b5b968043b913ed0f3020586a1e07b2.pdf\"\u003Ebest predictor of job performance\u003C\u002Fa\u003E&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EStill, you can take steps to raise your frustration tolerance and become more conscientious by working on your impulsivity. A non-conscientious person is &ldquo;up and gone&rdquo; the moment something challenging or uncomfortable comes up. &ldquo;What they have to do is invoke a volitional skill now. They have to be more conscious to stay in the moment &ndash; say, &lsquo;I have that tendency to do something else&rsquo;,&rdquo; says Pychyl.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"woman looking in fridge","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EHe recommends counting to five or taking five deep breaths &ndash; whatever strategy will &ldquo;keep the seat of [your] pants on [your] chair&rdquo;. Then, break the task into bite-sized, less frustrating bits to get you started, like opening a file or referencing an email. It&rsquo;ll be easier to get down to work &ndash; without getting distracted and walking away.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;All of this said, chronic procrastinators will procrastinate just about anywhere,&rdquo; Pychyl adds. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s just something that&rsquo;s inherent. It&rsquo;s just your disposition, and it&rsquo;s not going to change overnight.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWalk the line\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOne problem that people working from home are experiencing at the moment &ndash; both skilled remote workers and those new to telework &ndash; is a lack of boundaries. Your kitchen table might be both your desk and where you prepare dinner, which means you don&rsquo;t have what&rsquo;s called \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Flink.springer.com\u002Farticle\u002F10.1007\u002Fs12144-013-9171-8\"\u003E&lsquo;domain specificity&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in which to calibrate behaviour.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor instance, you handle tasks a certain way in your office; the same goes for when you get back home. These approaches are likely different, since you take on different \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.aom.org\u002Fdoi\u002F10.5465\u002Famj.2013.0991\"\u003E&lsquo;role identities&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E in each separate environment. But when work and personal matters are occurring in the same space, there are no cues for you to behave the way you do at work while you are outside your physical office.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThose who work well from home create boundaries in a work-life world without them, says Pychyl. &ldquo;Oftentimes, it&rsquo;s like, when I finish this cup of coffee then I&rsquo;m going to go to work. You put the cue for the action into the environment as a way to start structuring the unstructured environment.&rdquo; Then, once these parameters are established, people who commit fewer \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bc.edu\u002Fcontent\u002Fdam\u002Ffiles\u002Fcenters\u002Fcwf\u002Frt\u002Fpdf\u002FKreiner.%202009.pdf\"\u003E&lsquo;boundary violations&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are better off.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"man working in kitchen","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most productive remote workers also know they don&rsquo;t have to be tethered to their desks in order to set boundaries and delineate work from leisure. They&rsquo;re better at what are called \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fjournals.aom.org\u002Fdoi\u002F10.5465\u002Famr.2000.3363315\"\u003E&lsquo;micro-transitions&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E between tasks and environments, says Jean-Nicolas Reyt, assistant professor of organisational behaviour at McGill University in Montreal.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThat means you can get up and walk the dog, but you then have to set another boundary the moment you get back to work for a specific amount of time, or tackle a specific task uninterrupted. &ldquo;You don&rsquo;t have to commute for an hour and a half to transition,&rdquo; says Reyt. What matters, he says, it just getting in the habit of practicing creating those hard lines.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGetting &lsquo;energy shots&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe way in which people derive their energy could be a factor in remote productivity.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHighly social, extroverted people may have a more difficult time working from home without the &ldquo;water-cooler chat&rdquo;, says Matthew Davis, associate professor&nbsp;at Leeds University Business School. Those who rely on their social environment to enjoy their jobs, stave off monotony and keep up motivation may find themselves disadvantaged, he adds. Some literature shows this could make \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpdfs.semanticscholar.org\u002F37ac\u002F20804b5b968043b913ed0f3020586a1e07b2.pdf\"\u003Eextroverts especially dislike remote work\u003C\u002Fa\u003E &ndash; and could even affect telework performance.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Those who rely on their social environment to enjoy their jobs, stave off monotony and keep up motivation may find themselves disadvantaged","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EJulie Morgenstern, a New York-based productivity and organisation consultant , and the author of the best-selling book Never Check Email in the Morning, adds that &ldquo;if you&rsquo;re by yourself all day, you just don&rsquo;t get those energy shots, which can make it hard to feel motivated and focused&rdquo;. If you&rsquo;re flagging without social interaction, says Davis, set up regular calls with colleagues.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIs being an introvert in a home-work environment far better then? Not necessarily, says Davis. Even though they may thrive working alone, introverts can find video calls difficult due to discomfort with being the sole focus of a camera as well as speaking up in group chats. Especially as video calls become more common, Morgenstern adds that a successful worker needs to engage with their teammates on camera to connect with colleagues and gain essential non-verbal information such as body language cues.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs such, a balance of introversion and extroversion qualities may be a sweet spot for productivity, say both Davis and Morgenstern. There&rsquo;s a lot of alone time in telework, which energises introverts; on the other hand, extroverts can gain energy from team interaction.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"video call","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENose to the grindstone\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIf you&rsquo;re not as good at working from home as you wish you were, take solace in the fact that few people &ndash; even those remote-working pros &ndash; are working to their full potential in stressful times. It may be hard to compartmentalise the stress around you&shy; &ndash; especially when you&rsquo;re stuck at home &ndash; but the more you can adjust to your &lsquo;new normal&rsquo;, the better work-from-home employee you&rsquo;ll be, says Pychyl.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETry not to be frustrated if others are taking to the situation better than you; the transition may come more easily to people who are naturally more organised and disciplined, says Davis. For others, &ldquo;there needs to be some honest self-reflection in terms of what went well today, when did I struggle and then an attempt to identify what it was that knocked you off course&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EPractising can make perfect &ndash; but you&rsquo;ll only get better at telework if you actually find strategies to create boundaries and reel yourself in in other ways. &ldquo;Practice will help,&rdquo; adds Davis, &ldquo;but only if you have a strategy.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others-10"}],"collection":[],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-05-08T23:30:16Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Why are some people better at working from home than others?","headlineShort":"How to be better at working from home","image":[],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"worklife","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":[],"summaryLong":"In a world of telework, some people just take better to working from home. Does this productivity come naturally, or can you learn it?","summaryShort":"Why some people are naturally good at working remotely","tag":null,"creationDateTime":"2020-05-07T19:34:43.245769Z","entity":"article","guid":"79cac2ee-a108-4c7b-ba5e-55d596ec83e9","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others","modifiedDateTime":"2020-05-07T19:41:58.596201Z","project":"worklife","slug":"20200506-why-are-some-people-better-at-working-from-home-than-others","cacheLastUpdated":1590533223630},"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus","_id":"5ecace55c1ee0bf63c91148a","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["worklife\u002Fauthor\u002Fchristine-ro"],"bodyIntro":"From ‘covidiots’ to ‘quarantine and chill’, the pandemic has led to many terms that help people laugh and commiserate.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThroughout history, challenging circumstances have given rise to new ways of expressing those challenges. George Eliot, the 19th Century writer who was famously frustrated by rigid gender and lifestyle norms, is credited with the \u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fculture\u002Fstory\u002F20200507-the-women-who-created-a-new-language\"\u003Efirst recorded use of the word &lsquo;frustrating&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. More recently, Brexit led to a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fculture\u002Farticle\u002F20190314-how-brexit-changed-the-english-language?referer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.google.com%2F\"\u003Eflowering of new\u003C\u002Fa\u003E words, including the inevitable &lsquo;Bremain&rsquo; and &lsquo;Bregret&rsquo;, and a repurposing of existing words, such as &lsquo;backstop&rsquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhile Brexit may be the closest parallel, the speed of the linguistic change we&rsquo;re seeing with Covid-19 is unprecedented, says Robert Lawson, a sociolinguist at Birmingham City University. Lawson attributes this to multiple factors: the dizzying pace at which the virus has spread, its dominance in the media and global interconnectivity at a time when \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200408-coronavirus-how-lockdown-helps-those-who-fear-the-phone\"\u003Esocial media and remote contact are so important\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EMany of the newly popular terms relate to the socially distanced nature of human contact these days, such as &lsquo;virtual happy hour&rsquo;, &lsquo;covideo party&rsquo; and &lsquo;quarantine and chill&rsquo;. Many use &lsquo;corona&rsquo; as a prefix, whether Polish speakers convert &lsquo;coronavirus&rsquo; into a verb or English speakers wonder how &lsquo;coronababies&rsquo; (the children born or conceived during the pandemic) will fare. And, of course, there are abbreviations, like the ubiquitous &lsquo;WFH&rsquo; and the life-saving &lsquo;PPE&rsquo;.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOld words in a new light\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ELike everyone else, lexicologists are scrambling to keep up with the changes the pandemic has wrought. According to Fiona McPherson, the senior editor of the Oxford English Dictionary (OED), back in December &lsquo;coronavirus&rsquo; appeared only 0.03 times per million tokens (tokens are the smallest units of language collected and tracked in the OED corpus). The term &lsquo;Covid-19&rsquo; was only coined in February, when the WHO announced the official name of the virus. But in April, the figures for both &lsquo;Covid-19&rsquo; and &lsquo;coronavirus&rsquo; had skyrocketed to about 1,750 per million tokens (suggesting that the two terms are now being used at roughly the same frequency).\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08dwg1n"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"A sign warning 'covidiots' to go home in Barry, UK, on 25 March 2020","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpublic.oed.com\u002Fupdates\u002Fnew-words-list-april-2020\u002F\"\u003EAll of the terms added to the OED in April\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, in an unscheduled update, were related to the pandemic in some way, including &lsquo;infodemic&rsquo; and &lsquo;elbow bump&rsquo;. But McPherson notes that \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpublic.oed.com\u002Fupdates\u002F\"\u003Ethe only actual new word added to the dictionary is &lsquo;Covid-19&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The others are pre-existing terms that have gained new resonance at a time when many people are subject to a \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpublic.oed.com\u002Fblog\u002Fcircuit-breakers-ppes-veronica-buckets-world-englishes-covid-19\u002F\"\u003E&lsquo;stay-at-home order&rsquo; (US), &lsquo;movement control order&rsquo; (Malaysia) or &lsquo;enhanced community quarantine&rsquo; (Philippines)\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Although a lot of the words we&rsquo;re using just now and a lot of the terminology is actually older, a lot of it seems fairly new. &lsquo;Coronavirus&rsquo; itself goes back to the 1960s,&rdquo; she points out.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhat McPherson calls the &ldquo;nuancing of already existing words&rdquo; can in some cases be subtly harmful. War metaphors invoking &lsquo;battles&rsquo; and &lsquo;front-lines&rsquo; are being widely applied to the pandemic, yet thinking only in terms of a wartime emergency \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200430-covid-19-what-we-can-learn-from-wartime-efforts\"\u003Ecan detract from longer-term structural changes needed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. This has given rise to the project \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fsites.google.com\u002Fview\u002Freframecovid\u002Fhome\"\u003E#ReframeCovid\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, in which linguists collect crowdsourced examples of alternatives to war language.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIn&eacute;s Olza, a linguist at the University of Navarra in Spain, says she started the project spontaneously on Twitter. She understands the temptation to invoke war metaphors, especially at the start of the pandemic when they were necessary to build unity and mobilise swiftly. But &ldquo;a sustained use of that metaphor and abuse of it, and the lack of alternative frames, might generate anxiety and might distort things about the pandemic&rdquo;, she believes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;As well, terms such as \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.popsci.com\u002Fno-such-thing-as-natural-disaster\u002F\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E&lsquo;natural disaster&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E and \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.nejm.org\u002Fdoi\u002Ffull\u002F10.1056\u002FNEJMp2005032?query=TOC\" target=\"_blank\"\u003E&lsquo;perfect storm&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E can create the impression that the pandemic was inevitable and unavoidable, neglecting the political, economic and environmental contexts that make \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Ffuture\u002Farticle\u002F20200420-coronavirus-why-some-racial-groups-are-more-vulnerable\"\u003Ecertain people more exposed\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Some healthcare workers have expressed their \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.kevinmd.com\u002Fblog\u002F2020\u002F03\u002Fim-a-physician-and-im-not-a-hero.html\"\u003Efrustration at being called &lsquo;heroes&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, rather than seen as complex, frightened individuals doing a job, who need protective equipment and policy rather than relying on their own sacrifices.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08dwghk"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"A health care worker holds a placard in Burbank, US, on 19 May 2020","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Speakers are free to use the metaphors they want,&rdquo; Olza emphasises. &ldquo;We are not censors.&rdquo; But she and some of her fellow linguists believe that it&rsquo;s useful to reflect on language and to have alternative framings for discussing the pandemic &ndash; beyond militaristic language that can obscure the roles of individuals and communities, and toward expressions that communicate collective care and individual responsibility. She says that Germans have been especially good at finding non-war terms. German&rsquo;s compounding of terms, for instance, has allowed for one-off words like \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.zeit.de\u002Fpolitik\u002Fdeutschland\u002F2020-04\u002Fangela-merkel-lockerungen-corona-beschraenkungen-kritik-oeffnungsdiskussion\"\u003E&lsquo;&Ouml;ffnungsdiskussionsorgien&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E (&lsquo;orgies of discussion&rsquo;) to describe the seemingly endless policy debates over reopening.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhy humour helps\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EOverall, there&rsquo;s a wealth of linguistic creativity that hasn&rsquo;t yet entered the dictionary, but reflects \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Ftheconversation.com\u002Fcoronavirus-has-led-to-an-explosion-of-new-words-and-phrases-and-that-helps-us-cope-136909\"\u003Ethe role of novel language as a coping mechanism\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. These innovative usages, Lawson says, &ldquo;allow us to name whatever it is that&rsquo;s going on in the world. And once you can name the practices, the events, the social conditions around a particular event, it just gives people a shared vocabulary that they can all use as a bit of a shorthand. I think ultimately if you can name it, you can talk about it; and if you can talk about it, then it can help people cope and get a handle on really difficult situations&rdquo;.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWriter Karen Russell has found the newly ubiquitous term &lsquo;flatten the curve&rsquo; to be reassuring &ndash; a reminder of the importance of both individual and collective action, which \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.newyorker.com\u002Fmagazine\u002F2020\u002F04\u002F13\u002Fa-temporary-moment-in-time\"\u003E&ldquo;alchemizes fear into action&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. And both the practice and the terminology of \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.visualthesaurus.com\u002Fcm\u002Fwordroutes\u002Fnew-virus-new-words\u002F\"\u003E&lsquo;caremongering&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, used for instance in Canadian and Indian English, allow for an alternative to scaremongering.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBeyond earnest words like these, a kind of slightly anxious humour is central to many of the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Flanguage-and-innovation.com\u002F2020\u002F03\u002F31\u002Fcoronaspeak-the-language-of-covid-19-goes-viral\u002F\"\u003E&lsquo;coronacoinages&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The German &lsquo;coronaspeck&rsquo;, like the English &lsquo;Covid 19&rsquo;, playfully refers to \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200331-how-to-eat-a-healthy-diet-when-work-from-home-coronavirus\"\u003Estress eating amid stay-at-home orders\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. The Spanish &lsquo;covidiota&rsquo; and &lsquo;coronaburro&rsquo; (a play on &lsquo;burro&rsquo;, the word for donkey) poke fun at the people disregarding public health advice. \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.dictionary.com\u002Fe\u002Fs\u002Fnew-words-we-created-because-of-coronavirus\u002F#doom-scrolling\"\u003E&lsquo;Doomscrolling&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E describes the hypnotic state of endlessly reading grim internet news. Lawson&rsquo;s favourite, &lsquo;Blursday&rsquo;, captures the weakening sense of time when so many days bleed into each other.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"I don’t think that by having a little bit of light in the dark, people are making light of the situation - Fiona McPherson","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EAustralian English, no stranger to light-hearted abbreviations, has produced \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.visualthesaurus.com\u002Fcm\u002Fwordroutes\u002Fnew-virus-new-words\u002F\"\u003E&lsquo;quaz&rsquo; for &lsquo;quarantine&rsquo; and &lsquo;sanny&rsquo; for &lsquo;sanitiser&rsquo;\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Queer and black communities, so often a wellspring of linguistic innovation, have given rise to &lsquo;Miss Rona&rsquo; as a slang term for the virus. And for the unsayable, there are always emojis. The folded hands emoji, the medical mask emoji, and the microbe emoji (yes, that exists) have all \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fblog.emojipedia.org\u002Fspread-of-the-coronavirus-emoji\u002F\"\u003Ebecome more popular during the pandemic\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ESome of these emojis and terms might seem flippant, but &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think that by having a little bit of light in the dark, people are making light of the situation&rdquo;, says McPherson. Lawson agrees: &ldquo;If you can laugh at them, it makes things more manageable almost, and just helps with people&rsquo;s psychological health more than anything else.&rdquo;&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ELinguists believe that many of the terms currently in vogue won&rsquo;t endure. The ones with a stronger chance of sticking around post-pandemic are those that describe lasting behavioural changes, such as &lsquo;zoombombing&rsquo;, which is influenced by &lsquo;photobombing&rsquo; and describes the practice of invading someone else&rsquo;s video call. McPherson reckons that &lsquo;zoombombing&rsquo; could become a generic term (like &lsquo;hoovering&rsquo; up a mess) even if the company Zoom loses its market dominance.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EIngenuity with vocabulary can also communicate that the current hardships, like many of the coronacoinages, won&rsquo;t last forever. Olza has taken to referring to the tasks on her &lsquo;corona-agenda&rsquo;, which can be a subtle way of asking for people&rsquo;s patience with her temporarily disrupted schedule. Eventually &ldquo;I will get my usual agenda back,&rdquo; she says hopefully.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EUntil then, bring on the quarantinis.&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus-6"}],"collection":null,"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-05-25T00:00:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Why we’ve created new language for coronavirus","headlineShort":"Why we create new words in a crisis","image":["p08dwfpz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"Covid-19, spelled out using blocks","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5ec24d8cc1ee0bf63cc3ac8c"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"worklife","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"Covid-19, spelled out using blocks","promoImage":["p08dwfpz"],"relatedStories":["worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200520-will-coronavirus-change-germans-love-of-cash","worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200519-why-you-might-be-missing-your-commute","worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200514-how-the-post-pandemic-office-will-change"],"relatedTag":["tag\u002Fmodern-language"],"summaryLong":"From ‘covidiots’ to ‘quarantine and chill’, the pandemic has led to many terms that help people laugh and commiserate.","summaryShort":"From ‘covidiots’ to ‘Blursday’: How new words help us cope","tag":["tag\u002F20141118-language","tag\u002Fcovid-19"],"creationDateTime":"2020-05-24T19:42:57.647353Z","entity":"article","guid":"84dded55-cafc-49ac-b37f-594bd09a6168","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus","modifiedDateTime":"2020-05-24T19:42:57.647353Z","project":"worklife","slug":"20200522-why-weve-created-new-language-for-coronavirus","cacheLastUpdated":1590533223628},"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal","_id":"5ecd751cc1ee0bf63ca25c21","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["worklife\u002Fauthor\u002Fpeter-rubinstein"],"bodyIntro":"Stay-at-home orders are starting to lift and many are returning to work. But why do we feel anxious about resuming our usual routines?","businessUnit":"public service","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EEver since we were first confined to our homes, we&rsquo;ve daydreamed about the return to normal life, from the exhilarating to the mundane. We want to visit our favourite pubs, theatres or shops, and we suddenly feel an odd nostalgia for taking the train, trying on new clothes or even \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200413-coronavirus-will-covid-19-end-the-handshake\"\u003Eshaking hands\u003C\u002Fa\u003E.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBut as mandatory lockdowns around the world start to ease and businesses slowly open their doors, many of us who are not healthcare providers or essential workers are facing a puzzling dilemma: we feel anxious about resuming our normal routines, even though they&rsquo;re precisely what we&rsquo;ve been looking forward to.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWe can&rsquo;t predict exactly how our workplaces and commutes will change to combat coronavirus risks. Still, as we gear up to resume life outside the home, understanding the causes behind our apprehension is key to successfully managing the transition when the time finally comes.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhat, exactly, makes us feel uneasy about our looming return to work? BBC Worklife spoke to Dr Karen Cassiday, clinical psychologist and managing director of The Anxiety Treatment Center of Greater Chicago, and Dr David Rosmarin, founder of the Center for Anxiety in New York and assistant professor in the Department of Psychiatry at Harvard Medical School, about the contributing factors. &nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELockdown is easing &ndash; but why aren&rsquo;t I jumping for joy?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EFor months, we have wallowed in a state of high existential uncertainty, which has resulted in an enormous amount of stress, says Cassiday. As infection rates dip and swell, orders from our local and national leaders shift and concern for the safety of our loved ones grows, living in a state of confusion and worry has become the norm. &ldquo;Our bodies have been stuck in a high idle mode of stress response and this results in feeling tired, sad, irritable and worn out,&rdquo; says Cassiday.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"We will still continue to suffer the same things that we are experiencing now, just with less social isolation – Karen Cassiday","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThese feelings won&rsquo;t magically disappear when lockdown lifts. For the foreseeable future, &ldquo;we will still continue to suffer the same things that we are experiencing now, just with less social isolation&rdquo;, she says. This is part of the reason why, for many of us, the idea of resuming our normal routines isn&rsquo;t sparking positivity.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhen tackling a problem, having a defined role can make us feel like we&rsquo;re more in control of the situation, adds Cassiday. But due to the nature of the pandemic, we&rsquo;ve been forced into a position of powerlessness. &ldquo;We are, in effect, being asked to do nothing by staying at home&hellip; We all cope better with uncertainty when we feel like there is something specific that we can do to make things better and solve a problem.&rdquo; Returning to work may provide structure to our days, but it will not remedy this feeling of powerlessness over the pandemic.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAnd despite the downsides of living in quarantine, the few benefits that \u003Cem\u003Ehave\u003C\u002Fem\u003E emerged will make the transition back to work even more stressful when they&rsquo;re taken away, says Rosmarin. &ldquo;More sleep due to less commuting and working time, more time with family and less social pressure&rdquo; are things many of us will miss once lockdown lifts.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;So, if people have mixed emotions about the &lsquo;return to normal&rsquo; that seems perfectly healthy and expected to me,&rdquo; he says.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIs it OK to feel a bit emotionally exhausted?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;Definitely and a half,&rdquo; says Rosmarin. Even after lockdown lifts, he expects symptoms of depression, anxiety, irritability and even anger to persist for several months &ndash; in many cases triggered by \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.cfr.org\u002Fin-brief\u002Fdouble-pandemic-domestic-violence-age-covid-19\"\u003Erelationship troubles\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, which can be exacerbated by such a long period in close quarters.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;There are clear trends that marital strife and even domestic abuse have been on the rise,&rdquo; says Rosmarin, &ldquo;especially in families that were struggling before the pandemic.&rdquo; For the millions who have \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fbusiness-52591262\"\u003Elost work\u003C\u002Fa\u003E or been furloughed, the financial insecurity has only intensified emotional exhaustion. Parents are having to decide when children should return to school and if facilities are opening up. There&rsquo;s also navigating the process of working out what&rsquo;s best not just for you, but for those you love &ndash; it&rsquo;ll likely is continue through the summer and beyond.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08dvhpz"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWork pressure, meanwhile, may not have let up; people who find themselves caught in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200421-why-zoom-video-chats-are-so-exhausting\"\u003Eendless work-related Zoom meetings\u003C\u002Fa\u003E are no more immune to mental fatigue. &ldquo;The strain of trying to read other people's expressions and interact when there is a short time delay due to the video feed is very tiring,&rdquo; says Cassiday. &ldquo;We have to expend more effort just to interact on videoconferencing than we would if we were face to face or on a phone call.&rdquo; The stress that comes from these kinds of interactions also elevates our cortisol levels, which can in turn disrupt the quality of our sleep and moods, she adds.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ECassiday and Rosmarin agree that it won&rsquo;t be easy to shake lockdown-induced exhaustion as we begin to readjust to a standard routine &ndash; and that it&rsquo;s okay to ease into the transition. &ldquo;This has been a bona fide international crisis of the highest order and the disruption will likely have impact [sic] on our emotional states for some time,&rdquo; says Rosmarin.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EI&rsquo;m worried about being around more people &ndash; why is that?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBeing confined to our homes has allowed us to shift into a quieter and more peaceful pace of living, says Cassiday, so returning to commuting may seem unappealing. &ldquo;The truth is that rushing to work and standing in crowded trains is stressful and very likely not an ideal situation for any person,&rdquo; she says, and is one reason &ldquo;many people preferred to work from home part-time prior to the pandemic&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs we return to public transport and our offices, we will likely be forced to interact with these shared spaces in \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fworklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200514-how-the-post-pandemic-office-will-change\"\u003Enew ways\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Scientists predict that social distancing guidelines will stay in place until a vaccine is produced or herd immunity occurs, \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.bbc.com\u002Fnews\u002Fhealth-51665497\"\u003Ewhich will take time\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, says Cassiday. Until then, the procedures and etiquette within common areas will feel unfamiliar.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The lack of stress associated with getting up early to be on time and perform at work has been a huge stress relief – David Rosmarin","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;We may also be returning to workplaces that have lost workers to Covid-19 whom we could not properly mourn,&rdquo; she adds. &ldquo;We now have the task of changing our perspective from a short-term &lsquo;trying to flatten the curve&rsquo; mentality to a long-term &lsquo;new normal coping with a world pandemic&rsquo; mentality.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ERosmarin has learned from his patients that there are also some advantages to quarantine that may disappear with a return to the workplace. Many who suffer from shyness or social anxiety have fared &ldquo;well&rdquo; during lockdown because they have been able to avoid their fears of social interaction, he says. For others who struggle with depression, &ldquo;the lack of stress associated with getting up early to be on time and perform at work has been a huge stress relief&rdquo;.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;I don&rsquo;t think we should or can judge anyone for having mixed feelings about getting back to work,&rdquo; he adds.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWhat are the best ways to handle my anxiety through this period?\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhen we resume our routines, we must remember that attempting to minimise our anxiety about the transition will only make it more difficult. The goal should not be to pretend the anxiety doesn&rsquo;t exist or to race towards a feeling of normality, &ldquo;but rather to accept that it&rsquo;s present and bravely choose to exist and thrive with one&rsquo;s anxiety,&rdquo; says Rosmarin.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EHe encourages people with social anxiety &minus; perhaps reinforced by this long period of isolation &minus; to &ldquo;approach strangers, speak with their bosses, or otherwise do things that make them uncomfortable&rdquo; when lockdown lifts. Anxiety doesn&rsquo;t kill, he says, but our reactions to it can shape how resilient we are going forward. &ldquo;If right away when we recognise that it&rsquo;s coming, we simply brace ourselves and posture towards acceptance, it tends to decrease.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The brain and body cannot tell the difference between a false alarm and a true alarm for danger – Karen Cassiday","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003ECassiday says we must also understand that the &ldquo;brain and body cannot tell the difference between a false alarm and a true alarm for danger. It reacts the same to a scary movie as it does to your near miss of being hit by a bus&rdquo;. By recognising that anxiety is a signal for a \u003Cem\u003Epotential\u003C\u002Fem\u003E danger, and not necessarily an imminent threat to our safety, we can begin to use relaxation techniques like yoga, meditation or prayer to abate the feeling.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EAs we return to our commutes, workplaces and the outside world, Rosmarin says that feeling uneasy and ungrounded will be part of the &lsquo;new normal&rsquo; for some time. And although we&rsquo;re sure to face varying levels of anxiety as we go through the motions, we should take solace in the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.prevention.com\u002Fhealth\u002Fmental-health\u002Fa32332437\u002Fanxiety-disorder-during-coronavirus-pandemic\u002F\"\u003Enewfound acceptance and inclusivity\u003C\u002Fa\u003E around mental health struggles that have developed in the wake of the pandemic.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&ldquo;This crisis has shown us that &lsquo;normal&rsquo; means that we are human beings,&rdquo; says Rosmarin. &ldquo;We struggle with challenges, and that&rsquo;s OK.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal-8"}],"collection":null,"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-05-27T16:16:00Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"Why do we feel uneasy about a ‘new normal’?","headlineShort":"Why we're anxious about resuming work","image":["p08dvhm6"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"latitude":"","location":null,"longitude":"","mpsVideo":"","option":[{"Content":{"Description":"Apple News Publish: Select to publish, remove to unpublish. (Do not just delete or unpublish the story)","Name":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Metadata":{"CreationDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Entity":"option","Guid":"13f4bc85-ae27-4a34-9397-0e6ad3619619","Id":"option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","ModifiedDateTime":"2016-02-05T14:32:31.186819Z","Project":"","Slug":"publish-applenews-system-1"},"Urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:option:option\u002Fpublish-applenews-system-1","_id":"5ec24d8cc1ee0bf63cc3ac8c"}],"partner":null,"primaryVertical":"worklife","promoAlignment":"centre","promoAltText":"","promoImage":null,"relatedStories":null,"relatedTag":null,"summaryLong":"Stay-at-home orders are starting to lift and many are returning to work. But why do we feel anxious about resuming our usual routines?","summaryShort":"Lifting lockdown makes us worry. Here's why","tag":["tag\u002Fcovid-19"],"creationDateTime":"2020-05-26T19:59:07.007943Z","entity":"article","guid":"7f5f0ae7-e8ea-46c5-a1d9-6d4b2a61745f","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal","modifiedDateTime":"2020-05-26T19:59:07.007943Z","project":"worklife","slug":"20200521-why-do-we-feel-uneasy-about-a-new-normal","cacheLastUpdated":1590533223627},"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work":{"urn":"urn:pubstack:jative:article:worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work","_id":"5ecd37b5c1ee0bf63c6f454e","ambientVideo":"","articleType":"story","assetVideo":null,"author":["wwcapital\u002Fauthor\u002Fdavid-robson"],"bodyIntro":"It’s good to talk, but periods of silence are essential for problem solving.","businessUnit":"worldwide","cards":[{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EIf you &ndash; like many people across the world &ndash; are now working remotely, you might be worrying about loss of facetime with your team. Remote collaboration tools might help us to make up for this by allowing regular communication throughout the working day &ndash; and it would seem to make sense to take advantage of that connectivity with constant updates about your progress.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EYet the latest psychological literature suggests that less communication might actually be more: constant collaboration can in fact \u003Cem\u003Ereduce\u003C\u002Fem\u003E &lsquo;collective intelligence&rsquo; (a team&rsquo;s joint problem-solving ability). Instead of always staying in touch with colleagues with continual chats on Slack, say, we should aim to concentrate group communication to short, intermittent bursts &ndash; a single daily video call, for example &ndash; to boost team problem solving and creativity.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EBesides helping us to make better use of our time during the current crisis, these findings could help to shape the ways that we go about team decision making in the future. Even if we are in the office, we might all benefit from having a bit more me time and a bit less team time.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJumping to conclusions\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis new understanding of group communication has been years in the making. Jesse Shore at Boston University kicked things off in 2015, with a study that explored \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpubsonline.informs.org\u002Fdoi\u002Fpdf\u002F10.1287\u002Forsc.2015.0980\"\u003Ethe role of people&rsquo;s connectivity during group problem solving.\u003C\u002Fa\u003E Put simply, is it useful for everyone to be talking to everyone else, so we all know what&rsquo;s going in in every part of the team? Or is it sometimes better to limit our communication to just a few individuals?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EShore and his colleagues set up 51 groups, each consisting of 16 people. They asked the groups to play an online whodunnit game, borrowed from one of the US Department of Defense&rsquo;s R&amp;D teams, in which participants find and piece together clues to discover to predict the who, what, where and when of a (fictional) terrorist attack.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"infographic","imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","pullQuoteImageAlignment":"centre","videoImageAlign":"centre","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-0"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08d09fx"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-1"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe participants were given a user interface to share their findings with other team members, but the researchers controlled exactly how many people within each group would see each person&rsquo;s updates. In some groups, each person&rsquo;s messages were passed on to the majority of their teammates; this was a bit like a group chat channel, broadcasting info to everyone. In others, the messages went to just a couple of other members. Those members could then choose to share it with another couple of people, but no one could broadcast to the whole team at once. In this way, it was a little more like email, where you might be more likely to pass on information to select individuals rather than cc&rsquo;ing everyone at every stage of the process. Messages can still pass through the whole group through a chain of communication, but each person is acting as a bit of a filter.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-2"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"Although you might expect that these teams would struggle to come to an agreement, the major problem was conformity: the team members quickly converged on a consensus without really exploring the other possibilities","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-3"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EInitially, in the information-gathering &lsquo;reconnaissance&rsquo; stage of the game, the more connected groups performed well: the ability to pass leads on to all the other members meant that the team quickly gathered lots of potential clues about the attack. But they soon lost that advantage when they had to piece that information together to form a coherent theory about the way the terrorist plot would take place. Although you might expect that these teams would struggle to come to an agreement, like a hung jury, the major problem was conformity: the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpubsonline.informs.org\u002Fdoi\u002Fpdf\u002F10.1287\u002Forsc.2015.0980\"\u003Eteam members quickly converged on a consensus\u003C\u002Fa\u003E without really exploring the other possibilities. &ldquo;People aren't brainstorming effectively &ndash; they're not going off in their own direction,&rdquo; explains Shore.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe less well-connected groups, in contrast, suffered a bit with the information gathering, but they were also less likely to reach a consensus too quickly. Without the immediate updates from all teammates, each member was instead more likely to build their own theories, meaning that there was a greater diversity of ideas available before the team as a whole settled on the best solution.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlone time\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThis finding, by itself, would suggest that teams might consider limiting the communication among members. A bit of chit chat is good, but you don&rsquo;t necessarily want to know what everyone else is doing during the more creative parts of the problem solving that require the generation and testing of lots of ideas.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EInspired by this result, Shore and his colleagues next examined \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.pnas.org\u002Fcontent\u002F115\u002F35\u002F8734\"\u003Ehow the rhythm of our communication can also influence our problem solving\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Even if you are working in a small group, you have the option to receive constant updates, or limit your communication to a few regular catch-ups &ndash; but which is best?\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003ETo find out, the researchers asked participants to find solutions to a classic puzzle known as the \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.wired.com\u002F2013\u002F01\u002Ftraveling-salesman-problem\u002F\"\u003E&ldquo;travelling salesman&rdquo; problem\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, in which they were given a map of 25 different cities and needed to work out the shortest journey passing through them all. It&rsquo;s best solved iteratively, as you play with different options &ndash; and often retracing your previous steps &ndash; to find the optimal path.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-4"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08d09l8"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-5"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EThe participants were divided into groups of three. Using an online interface, some groups were allowed to interact constantly &ndash; they had immediate feedback on the solutions their teammates were trying. Others had only intermittent communication between periods of independent work. And some &lsquo;groups&rsquo; had no internal communication at all &ndash; they spent all the time working by themselves.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe researchers measured the effects on two outcomes &ndash; the team&rsquo;s average performance, and the performance of the top performer within each team. (That&rsquo;s important in real-life work &ndash; you want everyone to perform better, but you don&rsquo;t want the top individuals to be dragged down by less able individuals either all.)\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-6"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"PullQuote","iFrameType":"","pullQuote":"The groups with continuous interaction had good average performance, but it flattened the performance of the top-performing individuals","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-7"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EOnce again, moderation was key. The groups with continuous interaction had good average performance, but it flattened the performance of the top-performing individuals. As the researchers had also seen in the previous experiment, the team members all tended to conform to mediocre solutions. &ldquo;The &lsquo;out-there&rsquo; ideas aren't really considered,&rdquo; Shore explains. &ldquo;And some of their ideas might actually be excellent, even if most of them might not be.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe people working independently had the opposite problem &ndash; there was lots of variation among people, with some brilliant solutions, but the worst performers didn&rsquo;t have the opportunity to benefit from others&rsquo; solutions, meaning that they dragged down the group average.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EThe intermittent communication turned out to be the &lsquo;Goldilocks&rsquo; outcome &ndash; it was just the right about of interaction for both these measures: the average performance of the group was high, without reducing the performance of the best member. &ldquo;The groups could build on the diversity of the ideas that were generated independently, and then integrate them,&rdquo; says Shore. &ldquo;It was the best of both worlds.&rdquo;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E&lsquo;Bursty&rsquo; communication\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EShore&rsquo;s results complement \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fpapers.ssrn.com\u002Fsol3\u002Fpapers.cfm?abstract_id=2384068\"\u003Ethe research of Anita Williams Woolley of Carnegie Mellon University\u003C\u002Fa\u003E. Woolley studied 260 software workers, divided into groups of five, who were tasked with designing a new medical algorithm over a 10-day contest. She found that teams working with \u003Ca href=\"https:\u002F\u002Fbehavioralscientist.org\u002Fbursty-communication-can-help-remote-teams-thrive\u002F\"\u003Eshort &ldquo;bursts&rdquo; of communication\u003C\u002Fa\u003E, followed by longer periods of silence, performed better than less intense conversations stretched out over a long time. Once again, it seems that intermittent updates are best.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-8"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[]},"cardType":"Image","iFrameType":"","image":["p08d09nc"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageOrientation":"landscape","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-9"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003EWoolley&rsquo;s team suggest that &ldquo;bursty&rdquo; communication could help maintain momentum and motivation in various ways. One is obvious to anyone who has tried to focus on a task while receiving a steady stream of DMs: dealing with all your communication in one go reduces distraction.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EShort but intense communication also helps to create feelings of enthusiasm, which can dissipate if you face a slow and steady drip feed of emails without immediate feedback. By synchroenising their communication to relatively short periods, the best groups could catch up on each other&rsquo;s progress, share ideas, and coordinate their activity going forward, enthusing each other in those interactions while still leaving enough time for intense concentration afterwards.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EGiven these results, it might be tempting to look for a hard-and-fast rule for the optimal level of communication, but the exact ratio of active collaboration and solitude almost certainly depends on the task at hand and the medium. You have to judge it on your own team dynamics for whether a daily Zoom call is necessary, for example; whether Slack use should be limited to certain stages of the project; or whether you are better sending a single round-up email rather than a stream of one-line messages.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003EWhat&rsquo;s clear, however, is that we probably don&rsquo;t need to be connected to each other all the time. Whether we are working remotely or in the office, it&rsquo;s good to talk &ndash; but sometimes our interactions with others are best taken in short doses.\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-10"},{"bodyHtml":{"assets":[],"html":"\u003Cp\u003E&nbsp;\u003C\u002Fp\u003E\n\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cem\u003EDavid Robson is the author of \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.davidrobson.me\u002Fthe-intelligence-trap\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe Intelligence Trap\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E,\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003E which examines why smart people act foolishly and the ways we can all make wiser decisions. He is \u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003Ca href=\"http:\u002F\u002Fwww.twitter.com\u002Fd_a_robson\"\u003E\u003Cem\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E@d_a_robson\u003C\u002Fstrong\u003E\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fa\u003E\u003Cem\u003E on Twitter.\u003C\u002Fem\u003E\u003C\u002Fp\u003E"},"cardType":"Body","iFrameType":"","id":"worklife\u002Farticle\u002F20200513-the-benefits-isolation-can-have-on-your-work-11"}],"collection":["worklife\u002Fcolumn\u002Fcollective-intelligence"],"disableAdverts":false,"displayDate":"2020-05-26T05:34:52Z","embeddedCustomHtml":"","embeddedInfographicUrl":"","embeddedType":"infographic","geolocation":null,"headlineLong":"The benefits isolation can have on your work","headlineShort":"Why isolation improves team performance","image":["p08f6s0j"],"imageAlignment":"centre","imageAltText":"","isSyndicated":true,"la